00:10:29,250 --> 00:10:30,541
he acknowledges

215
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:42,583
the Buddhist teaching of Anatta

216
00:10:42,583 --> 00:10:44,000
or no self stands as

217
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:47,041
one of the most radical propositions in human thought

218
00:10:47,250 --> 00:10:49,250
in the Anattalakkhana Sutta

219
00:10:49,541 --> 00:10:52,208
his second discourse after Enlightenment

220
00:10:52,583 --> 00:10:53,583
Buddha challenged

221
00:10:53,583 --> 00:10:56,041
the prevailing notion of an unchanging soul

222
00:10:56,041 --> 00:10:57,541
or self

223
00:11:12,416 --> 00:11:15,166
modern Buddhist scholar Bhikkhu Bodhi explains

224
00:11:15,166 --> 00:11:16,166
the Anatta doctrine

225
00:11:16,166 --> 00:11:18,500
is not a mere philosophical opinion

226
00:11:18,875 --> 00:11:22,208
but a strategy for seeing through the conceit of self

227
00:11:22,458 --> 00:11:25,041
and thereby letting go of all attachment

228
00:11:26,083 --> 00:11:28,625
this interpretation aligns with both classical

229
00:11:28,625 --> 00:11:29,541
commentaries

230
00:11:29,541 --> 00:11:32,208
and contemporary understanding of the teaching

231
00:11:32,708 --> 00:11:34,958
to understand this profound teaching

232
00:11:35,041 --> 00:11:40,250
we must first grasp what Buddha meant by self

233
00:11:40,958 --> 00:11:43,375
in ancient India the dominant

234
00:11:43,375 --> 00:11:46,500
Vedic tradition taught the existence of an eternal

235
00:11:46,500 --> 00:11:49,541
unchanging soul called Atman

236
00:11:50,375 --> 00:11:51,625
Buddha's direct experience

237
00:11:51,625 --> 00:11:53,958
through meditation revealed something different

238
00:11:54,375 --> 00:11:57,791
a dynamic flow of experience with no permanent center

239
00:11:58,708 --> 00:12:00,250
the Buddha used a practical method

240
00:12:00,250 --> 00:12:01,958
to demonstrate this truth

241
00:12:02,291 --> 00:12:05,583
he broke down human experience into five aggregates

242
00:12:05,708 --> 00:12:07,083
or skandhas

243
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:11,291
form feeling perception

244
00:12:11,625 --> 00:12:14,500
mental formations and consciousness

245
00:12:15,291 --> 00:12:17,500
through systematic examination

246
00:12:17,500 --> 00:12:19,375
he showed that none of these components

247
00:12:19,375 --> 00:12:23,291
alone or combined constitutes a permanent self

248
00:12:25,666 --> 00:12:27,000
consider a simple example

249
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:29,458
Buddha often used a chariot

250
00:12:30,041 --> 00:12:31,583
when we disassemble a chariot

251
00:12:31,583 --> 00:12:33,333
into its wheels axle

252
00:12:33,458 --> 00:12:35,208
body and reins

253
00:12:35,625 --> 00:12:37,625
